  "prompt": "How do you find the molar mass of CuSO4?",
  "response": "To find the molar mass of CuSO4 (copper(II) sulfate), you need to sum the molar masses of all the atoms in the compound. Here are the steps:\n\n1. **Identify the atomic masses of each element** typically from the periodic table:\n   - Copper (Cu): approximately 63.55 g/mol\n   - Sulfur (S): approximately 32.07 g/mol\n   - Oxygen (O): approximately 16.00 g/mol\n\n2. **Count the number of each type of atom in the formula** CuSO4:\n   - There is 1 atom of copper (Cu).\n   - There is 1 atom of sulfur (S).\n   - There are 4 atoms of oxygen (O).\n\n3. **Multiply the atomic masses by the number of atoms**:\n   - Copper: 63.55 g/mol \u00d7 1 = 63.55 g/mol\n   - Sulfur: 32.07 g/mol \u00d7 1 = 32.07 g/mol\n   - Oxygen: 16.00 g/mol \u00d7 4 = 64.00 g/mol\n\n4. **Add the results together** to get the total molar mass of CuSO4:\n   - 63.55 g/mol (Cu) + 32.07 g/mol (S) + 64.00 g/mol (O) = 159.62 g/mol\n\nTherefore, the molar mass of CuSO4 is approximately **159.62 g/mol**.",
